div.div:
For simplicity, support a `select where SVSpec` query iff there is an exact SI with the provided SVSpec.
1. Find the SI that has the SVSpec. If not found, fail.
2. Get range from the SI. Compare each (SV, PK) in index with user-provided SV. Return [ (PK, PV) ].
Note, whether the user query is for one SV or a range of SVs, the API of the SI is "get range", not "get one".

div.div:
A secondary index may abstract any of:
a) SortedMap< SV, [ PV ] >
b) SortedMap< (SV, PK), Opt<PV> >
c) SortedMap< (SV, PK), Opt<()> >
a) K-merging in SI would be more complicated than in PI.
b) option 1) "Clustered index" duplicates PV across all indexes (on disk and on memory).
b) option 2) Secondary SSTables do not duplicate PV, but point to a file offset within the primary SSTable. Range queries on SI require non-sequential disk read.
c) It requires n+1 index usages per "get by range of SVs" type of query.
Current impl is b) option 1).

div.div:
Concurrency guarantees:
If each user query is run in its own thread:
- There is no isolation, not even Read Uncommitted.
- Rollbacks race with other writes.
Alternative 1: If we remove support for transactions (e.g. RMW), then we would have Linearizable consistency.
Alternative 2: If we run queries serially, we have Serializable isolation + Linearizable consistency. Then, we would have only two threads: a) queries runner, b) GC job.
Locking order:
To avoid deadlocks, always lock "top" mutex first, then "bottom" mutex (or always vice versa).
This design is not implemented.
